MCMC

DAG and local probability distributions

# MCMC parameters
n_adapt = 1000
iter = 50000
# Example nodes
methyl = "cg00339319"
metab = "gctof_33"
temp = pair_data[,c("T1Dgroup",methyl,metab)]
temp = temp[complete.cases(temp),]
# Data (X[,1] must be methylation and X[,2] must be metabolite)
y = as.numeric(temp$T1Dgroup) - 1
X = temp[,c(methyl,metab)]
N = nrow(X)
# JAGS
jags_data = list(y=y,X=X,N=N)
mod = jags.model("./code/networks/omics_to_t1d_methyl_to_metab.jags",
                 data = jags_data, n.adapt = n_adapt,n.chains = 2,quiet = T)
suppressWarnings(cat(readLines('./code/networks/omics_to_t1d_methyl_to_metab.jags'),
                     sep = '\n'))
## model{
##   # metab | methyl
##   for (i in 1:N) {
##     X[i,2] ~ dnorm(gamma0 + gamma1*X[i,1], tau)
##     }
##   # T1D | methyl, metab
##   for (i in 1:N) {
##     y[i] ~ dbern(q[i])
##     logit(q[i]) <- beta0 + beta1*X[i,1] + beta2*X[i,2]
##     }
##   
##    # Very flat priors
##    beta0 ~ dnorm(0,0.0001)
##    beta1 ~ dnorm(0,0.0001)
##    beta2 ~ dnorm(0,0.0001)
##    gamma0 ~ dnorm(0,0.0001)
##    gamma1 ~ dnorm(0,0.0001)
## 
##   tau ~ dgamma(0.0001, 0.0001)
##   sigma2 <- 1/tau
##   }
## 
# MCMC
samples = coda.samples(mod,n.iter = iter,thin = 20,
                       variable.names = c("beta0","beta1","beta2","gamma0","gamma1"))
# Bayes output
output = MCMCsummary(samples,Rhat = F,HPD = T,hpd_prob = 0.8)
MCMCtrace(samples,pdf = F,iter = iter - n_adapt)

CIT Package

The CIT package is able to test two mediation structures with T1D status as the outcome:

CIT results from the same probe - metabolite pair as in the MCMC example above:

Single Permutation
p_cit p_T1D ~ methyl p_T1D ~ metab | methyl p_metab ~ methyl | T1D p_methyl indep. T1D | metab
0.2896414 0.0534403 0.2896414 0.0001996 0.17

Distibution of p values looks reasonable across permutations. The omnibus p value is elevated because it’s simply the highest of the four others.
